According to wheelchairtraveling.com: Old Fort Jackson, built in 1808, is another Civil War historical point of interest. It is located close to Downtown Savannah,  making it an easy visit. It is much smaller than Fort Pulaski, though it has its own unique charm. There’s a canon firing every day at 10 am and 2 pm from spring to summer. Visitors may also find locals dressed up as wartime characters. Visitors with limited mobility have access to the ground floor only.

Visitors who have a permanent disability get free admission. One parking spot in front of the ticket office and visitor center is designated as wheelchair-accessible. The trailhead is on the other end of the paved parking lot, so visitors may consider parking there instead. A wooden pathway leads inside the building (approximately 5% grade slope), but there are no automatic doors. The ticket office and gift shop is small. A little merchandise is for purchase as well as candy and other sweets.

The main walkway to Old Fort Jackson is paved and 5 feet wide or more; inside there is a mixture of pathways, but all are relatively accessible. Go left heading into the Fort; this way is pavement and the other option has old cobblestones. Keeping to the perimeter of the Fort, explore the ins and outs of building compartments; passageways may be too narrow for some wheelchairs and scooters. To see other areas of the Fort will require traveling over the courtyard lawn; which is firm but gets muddy with the rains. This side of the fort area has a wooden boardwalk pathway that wraps around the rest of the fort; one section is a dead-end for wheelchairs and scooters and requires some brief four-wheeling on the courtyard lawn.

Within the walls of the fort on the ground floor are separate restrooms for both men and women. It’s approximately 5 by 5 feet with grab-bars and a roll-up sink.

